{
  "result": "At dawn, the city is briefly honest. Delivery trucks mutter along the curb, bakery windows glow like small promises, and the first cyclists move through intersections as if they are testing whether the day will hold. I like this hour because nothing has fully declared itself. A meeting is still only a square on a calendar; an apology is still possible; rain is a rumor gathered in the blue-gray clouds.\n\nPeople often imagine change as a thunderclap, but most change arrives as a habit too small to respect. You put your shoes by the door. You drink water before coffee. You write one sentence in a notebook and stop before you can judge it. Weeks later, the sentence has become a page, the page a direction, the direction a life with slightly different weather.\n\nI am fond of ordinary tools: a pencil shaved to a clean point, a spoon worn thin at the lip, a key whose brass has learned the shape of a hand. They remind me that usefulness can be beautiful without announcing itself. The world is crowded with performances, yet quiet competence continues to save us: nurses checking charts, programmers naming variables, parents cutting fruit into moons, neighbors sweeping glass from the street.\n\nIf I could wish for everyone one gift, it would be attention: the patient kind that notices a loose button, a tired voice, a patch of weeds becoming flowers. Attention is love before it has chosen a name today for us all to share.",
